dren showed resilience in surviving the various types of discrimination common in this period. It will appeal to anyone interested in British social history, childhood studies, or legal history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIllegitimate childrenxLegal status, laws, etcxHistoryx19th centuryxEngland. 0aIllegitimate childrenxLegal status, laws, etcxHistoryx20th centuryxEngland. 0aIllegitimate childrenxLegal status, laws, etczEnglandxHistoryy19th century. 0aIllegitimate childrenxLegal status, laws, etczEnglandxHistoryy20th century. 0aIllegitimate childrenxLegal status, laws, etc.zEnglandxHistoryy19th century. 0aIllegitimate childrenxLegal status, laws, etc.zEnglandxHistoryy20th century. 0aIllegitimate childrenxSocial conditionsx19th centuryxEngland. 0aIllegitimate childrenxSocial conditionsx20th centuryxEnglandxEngland. 0aIllegitimate childrenzEnglandxSocial conditionsy19th century. 0aIllegitimate childrenzEnglandxSocial conditionsy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh  aEngland.  aVictorian children.  aWales.  aaffiliation suits.  abastardy laws.  achild circulation.  achild-saving groups.  acriminal courts.  afostering.  agender.  aillegitimacy.  alate-Victorian period.  alegitimacy.  amarried parents.  anon-maternal defendants.  apoor law.  asocial discrimination.  aunwanted children.  awar pensions.1 aFrost, Ginger S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2016 eBook-Packagez978311128282440uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978178499744140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781784997441423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781784997441/original  a978-3-11-128282-4  Manchester University Press 